y put forth a constructivist theory of knowledge. This shift in Kant’s thinking challenged the representational approach to epistemology, and it is this turn, Rockmore contends, that makes Kant the first great phenomenologist. He then follows this phenomenological line through the work of Kant’s idealist successors, Fichte and Hegel. Steeped in the sources and literature it examines, Kant and Phenomenology persuasively reshapes our conception of both of its main subjects.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aKnowledge, Theory of. 0aPhenomenology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aphilosophy, philosophical, immanuel kant, rationalism, empiricism, epistemology, politics, aesthetics, phenomenology, constructivism, knowledge, theory, structures of consciousness, perspective, intentionality, content, meaning, conditions, intentional, experience, phenomena, foundation, discipline, debates, debatable, ontology, perception.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022672340240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226723419423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226723419/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles